\begin_layout Section
From time scattering to spiral scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This section builds the spiral scattering transform progressively as a cascade of wavelet transforms along time, log-frequency, and octave index. All three variables share the same framework.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Time scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An analytic "mother" wavelet is a complex filter 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi(t)$
\end_inset

 whose Fou\SpecialChar \-
rier transform 
\begin_inset Formula $\widehat{\psi}(\omega)$
\end_inset

 is concentrated over the dimensionless frequency interval 
\begin_inset Formula $[1-Q/2,1+Q/2]$
\end_inset

, where the quality factor 
\begin_inset Formula $Q$
\end_inset

 is in the typical range 
\begin_inset Formula $12$
\end_inset

–
\begin_inset Formula $24$
\end_inset

. Dilations of this wavelet define a family of bandpass filters centered at frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $ \lambda_{1} = 2^{j_{1} + \frac{\chi_{1}}{Q}}$
\end_inset

, where the indices 
\begin_inset Formula $j_{1} \in \mathbb{Z}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\chi_{1} \in \{1\ldots\,Q\}$
\end_inset

 respectively denote octave and chroma: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    \widehat{\psi}_{\lambda_{1}}(\omega) = \widehat{\psi}(\lambda^{-1}\omega)
    \quad\mathrm{i.e.}\quad
    \psi_{\lambda_{1}}(t)=\lambda_{1}\psi(\lambda_{1}t).
\label{eq:wavelet-dilations}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelet transform convolves an input signal 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 with the filter bank of 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_1}$
\end_inset

's. We denote convolutions along time by the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{t}{\ast}$
\end_inset

. Applying complex modulus to all wavelet convolutions results in the "scalogram" matrix 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
    x_1(t, \log \lambda_1) =
    |x \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_1}| \quad \text{for all } \lambda_1 > 0,
\label{eq:scalogram}
\end{equation}
\end_inset

whose frequential axis is uniformly sampled by the binary logarithm 
\begin_inset Formula $\log \lambda_1$
\end_inset

. The scalogram 
\begin_inset Formula $x_1$
\end_inset

 localizes the energy of 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 around frequencies 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_1$
\end_inset

 over durations 
\begin_inset Formula $2 Q / \lambda_1$
\end_inset

, trading frequency resolution for time resolution.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The constant-Q transform (CQT) 
\begin_inset Formula $S_1 x$
\end_inset

 corresponds to a lowpass filtering of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_1$
\end_inset

 with a window 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_T(t)$
\end_inset

 of size 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

: 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_1 x (t, \log \lambda_1) =
x_1 \overset{t}{\ast} \phi_T =
| x \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{1}} | \overset{t}{\ast} \phi_T.
\label{eq:S1}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To recover the amplitude modulations lost when averaging by 
\begin_inset Formula $\phi_T$
\end_inset

 in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:S1"

\end_inset

), the time scattering transform also convolves 
\begin_inset Formula $x_1$
\end_inset

 with a second filterbank of wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_2}$
\end_inset

 and applies complex modulus to get 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x_2 (t, \log \lambda_1, \log \lambda_2) =
\vert x_1 \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_2} \vert =
\vert \vert x \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{1}} \vert
\overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{2}} \vert.
\label{eq:x2-time}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_2}(t)$
\end_inset

 have a quality factor in the range 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

–
\begin_inset Formula $2$
\end_inset

, though we choose to keep the same notation 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi$
\end_inset

 for simplicity. Like in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:S1"

\end_inset

), averaging in time creates invariance to translation in time up to 
\begin_inset Formula $T$
\end_inset

, yielding 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
S_2 x (t, \log \lambda_1, \log \lambda_2) =
x_2 \overset{t}{\ast} \phi_T =
\vert \vert x \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{1}} \vert
\overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{2}} \vert
\overset{t}{\ast} \phi_T.
\label{eq:S2-time}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Due to the constant-Q property, 
\begin_inset Formula $S_1 x$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $S_2 x$
\end_inset

 are stable to small time warps of 
\begin_inset Formula $x(t)$
\end_inset

 as long as they do not exceed 
\begin_inset Formula $Q^{-1}$
\end_inset

, i.e. one semitone. This implies that small modulations, such as tremolo and vibrato, are accurately linearized 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Anden2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Joint time-frequency scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time scattering transform defined in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:x2-time"

\end_inset

) decomposes each frequency band separately, and thus cannot properly capture the coherence of time-frequency structures, such as those induced by pitch contour. To remedy this, Andén et al. 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Anden2015"

\end_inset

 have redefined the wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_2}$
\end_inset

's as functions of both time and log-frequency, indexed by pairs 
\begin_inset Formula $\lambda_2 = (\alpha,\beta)$
\end_inset

, where 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is a modulation frequency in Hertz and 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta$
\end_inset

 is a frequency along log-frequencies in cycles per octaves. The joint wavelets 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{\lambda_2}(t,\log \lambda_1)$
\end_inset

 factorize as 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\psi_{\lambda_2}(t,\log \lambda_1) = \psi_\alpha (t) \times \psi_\beta (\log \lambda_1).
\label{eq:wavelet-joint}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We write 
\begin_inset Formula $\overset{\chi_{1}}{\ast}$
\end_inset

 to denote convolutions along the log-frequency axis, i.e. along chromas. Wavelet scattering is extended to two-dimensional convolutions by plugging Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:wavelet-joint"

\end_inset

) into the definition of 
\begin_inset Formula $x_2$
\end_inset

 in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:x2-time"

\end_inset

): 
\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
x_{2}(t,\log \lambda_{1},\log \lambda_{2}) =
\vert x_{1} \overset{t, \chi_{1}}{\ast} \psi_{\lambda_{2}} \vert =
\vert x_{1} \overset{t}{\ast} \psi_{\alpha} \overset{\chi_{1}}{\ast} \psi_{\beta} \vert.
\label{eq:x2-joint}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The joint time-frequency scattering transform corresponds to the "cortical transform" introduced by Shamma and his team to formalize his findings in auditory neuroscience 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Patil2012"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Spiral scattering
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The time-frequency scattering transform defined in Equation (
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "eq:x2-joint"

\end_inset

) provides template-free features for pitch variability along time. However, it is unaware of the harmonic structure of voiced sounds, such as vowels or musical notes. The multiscale evolution of this structure yields relevant information about attack transients and formantic changes, almost independently from the pitch contour.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In order to capture this information, we extend the joint time-frequency scattering transform to encompass regularity in time across octaves at fixed chroma, in conjunction with regularity along neighboring constant-Q bands. Just like wavelet filterbanks along time and log-frequency have been defined in the two previous subsections, we capitalize on harmonicity by introducing a third wavelet filterbank.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
We roll up the log-frequency variable 
\begin_inset Formula $\log \lambda_1$
\end_inset

 into a pitch spiral making one full turn at each octave (see Figure 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand ref
reference "fig:spiral-wavelets"

\end_inset

). Since a frequency interval of one octave corresponds to one unit in binary logarithms 
\begin_inset Formula $\log \lambda_1$
\end_inset

, pitch height and pitch chroma in the spiral correspond to integer part 
\begin_inset Formula $\lfloor \log \lambda_1 \rfloor$
\end_inset

 and fractional part 
\begin_inset Formula $\{ \log \lambda_1 \}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Formula \begin{equation}
\log \lambda_1 = \lfloor \log \lambda_1 \rfloor + \{ \log \lambda_1 \} = j_1 + \frac{\chi_1}{Q}.
\label{eq:integer-part and fractional part}
\end{equation}
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this setting, the fundamental frequency 
\begin_inset Formula $f_0$
\end_inset

 is aligned with its power-of-two harmonics 
\begin_inset Formula $2 f_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $4 f_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $8 f_0$
\end_inset

 and so forth. Likewise, the perfect fifth 
\begin_inset Formula $3 f_0$
\end_inset

 is aligned with 
\begin_inset Formula $6 f_0$
\end_inset

. As the number of harmonics per octave increase exponentially, the alignment of upper harmonics — 
\begin_inset Formula $5 f_0$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $7 f_0$
\end_inset

, and so forth — in the spiral is less crucial, because it can also be recovered with convolutions along chromas for 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

 of the order of a few semitones.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

\begin_inset Float figure
placement t
wide false
sideways false
status open


\begin_layout Standard
\align center

\begin_inset ERT
status collapsed

\begin_layout Plain Layout

\backslash
setlength{
\backslash
unitlength}{1cm}
\end_layout

\end_inset

 
