\begin_inset Caption Standard

\begin_layout Plain Layout
 Top: scalogram of a musical note from Berio's 
\emph on
Sequenza V
\emph default
 for trombone, around 3'45". Observe that the attack part (a) has increasing pitch and increasing brightness, whereas the release part (b) has decreasing pitch and decreasing brightness. Bottom: spiral scattering coefficients for 
\begin_inset Formula $t$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\log \lambda_1$
\end_inset

 specified by (a) and (b), 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha^{-1}$
\end_inset

 fixed at 46 ms, 
\begin_inset Formula $\beta^{-1}$
\end_inset

 ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $-1\text{ octave}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $+1\text{ octave}$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma^{-1}$
\end_inset

 ranging from 
\begin_inset Formula $-4\text{ octaves}$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $+1\text{ octaves}$
\end_inset

. As expected, highest values are concentrated in the bottom left corner for (a) and in the top right corner for (b). 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "fig:berio-scalogram"

\end_inset

 
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the example of a trombone signal, glissando can be modeled by 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\theta}(t) / \dot{\theta}(t)$
\end_inset

 in the source-filter model, whereas the brassiness profile induces a timbral velocity 
\begin_inset Formula $\ddot{\eta}(t) / \dot{\eta}(t)$
\end_inset

. Figure 3 illustrates that these two velocities are stably disentangled and characterized.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Conclusions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The spiral model we have presented is well-known in music theory and experimental psychology 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
after ""
key "Shepard1964, Risset1969, Deutsch2008"

\end_inset

. However, existing methods in audio signal processing do not fully take advantage from its richness, because they either picture pitch on a line (e.g. MFCC) or on a circle (e.g. chroma features). In this article, we have shown how spiral scattering can represent the transientness of harmonic sounds.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard

